<TEXT>
the debt crisis that has engulfed many 
developing countries is striking a blow at us agriculture 
shrinking the available supply of credit to purchase american 
commodities 
high interest rates declining commodity prices and currency 
devaluations in the 1980s have thrust much of the burden of the 
worlds economic problems on heavily indebted developing 
countries says an issue paper produced recently by usdas 
economic research service 
between 1975 and 1987 the total debt of all nonindustrial 
countries rose from 234 billion to about 12 trillion according 
to the authors mathew shane and david stallings it noted a jump 
in debt service payments in the early 1980s from about 12 percent 
of total exports to 25 percent 
latin american debt service payments have climbed from 20 
percent to 40 percent the paper said 
to compound matters commercial banks have withdrawn credit and 
the indebted nations have forced a reduction in imports while 
attempting to spur exports 
these moves to limit imports represent a serious problem for 
us farmers because the developing world represents the fastest 
growing market for agricultural exports 
imports of american farm products leveled off six years ago and 
there has been little change since a marked contrast to the 1970s 
when the developing worlds share of us exports ballooned from 25 
percent to more than 40 percent 
the united states has battled to maintain market share with 
federal programs to stimulate exports the issue paper describes as 
especially effective programs that guarantee credit to overseas 
customers it also points to food aid programs as particularly 
helpful 
nearly 50 percent of all us agricultural exports to the 
problem borrowers were shipped under federal export programs in 
1983 and remained above 40 percent through 1986 the paper said 
among countries that represent major markets for the united states 
about 30 percent of all us farm goods imported received 
government support 
the figure for latin america is 40 percent according to the 
paper while less than 15 percent of those to hong kong south 
korea and taiwan have been financed through such programs 
</TEXT>
