a frequent critic of federal air traffic 
control efforts says a new government report showing a reduction in 
near accidents is good news but he says the system remains under 
severe pressure 
were all happy to see it but by no means are we ready to 
celebrate sen frank lautenberg dnj chairman of the 
senates transportation appropriations subcommittee said monday 
after the federal aviation administration released its figures 
the faa said there were 518 operational errors by air traffic 
controllers during the first six months of this year an 18 percent 
drop from the 635 recorded in the first half of 1987 
the 366 aerial nearcollisions reported by pilots from january 
through june this year was a 27 percent decline from the 500 
reported during the same period in 1987 
in addition there were 60 reports of aircraft or ground 
vehicles entering active runways without permission during the 
first three months of 1988 27 percent fewer than the 82 tallied in 
the first quarter of 1987 
these numbers combined with the generally downward movement 
in aircraft accident rates in the first half of 1988 indicate a 
continued pattern of improvement in aviation safety faa 
administrator allan mcartor said in a statement 
but lautenberg said the figures showed encouraging numbers 
not satisfactory numbers 
he said a military plane he was in last friday flying to 
teterboro airport in new jersey had to veer off course to avoid 
colliding with another aircraft that his pilot later told him had 
been only 200 feet away 
the system is under strain he said 
the frequency of operational errors in which the required 
spacing between aircraft in flight is violated has been declining 
since the middle of last year 
but the number of aerial nearcollisions has begun declining for 
the first time in about five years faa spokesman john leyden said 
the agency defines a nearcollision as an incident in which two 
aircraft come within 500 feet of each other in flight or when 
flight crews believe a hazard of a collision existed 
public concern about safety in the skies peaked last year 
complaints from passengers surged airliners crashed at the detroit 
and denver airports and a helicopter carrying president reagan 
averted a collision with a small plane near his california ranch 
the government often under prodding from congress has taken 
steps such as hiring additional air traffic controllers changing 
flight procedures around the countrys largest airports and 
requiring expanded use of devices that report an aircrafts 
altitude 
i think we can take some credit for this record of 
improvement mcartor said 
