were not disagreeing with the corps on whether its needed or 
not said joseph farrell president of the american waterways 
operators but if the diversion proves to be necessary they say 
it wont have any effect 
the industry thinks them wrong 
inland barge and towboat operators already have lost 45 million 
to 60 million since june 15 because of the drought farrell said 
at a news conference monday he predicted they would lose 150 
million to 200 million 20 percent of their annual revenue even 
if conditions do not worsen 
although some smaller barge operators could be forced out of 
business because of losses farrell said he knew of none which have 
folded so far and is unaware of layoffs 
he also said executives of major shipping firms unanimously 
agreed after reviewing loss projections that they would not seek 
government relief in the form of grants loans or a fuel tax 
exemption 
the industry feels that this is one of the risks of 
business he said 
unprecedented lowwater levels are making it impossible to move 
t oload them as heavily and farrell 
said shorter lighter tows are taking twice the usual time to reach 
their destinations 
the effect is on the bottom line he said time is always 
money 
for example he said it now takes 28 to 30 days to make what 
customarily is a twoweek trip pushing grain barges from processing 
plants in minneapolis to new orleans for shipment overseas 
the lower mississippi downriver from the confluence of the 
missouri and the ohio is experiencing the worst problems because 
it has no lockanddam system to hold back water and maintain 
higher levels he said 
the ohio has got locks and dams up and down its length 
because of that the ability to regulate the flow has made that not 
a critical problem farrell said its the same with the 
missouri 
the mississippi at new orleans currently is flowing at a rate of 
90000 cubic feet per second down from the normal rate of 500000 
cubic feet and the corps of engineers does not expect the flow to 
drop further farrell said 
assistant secretary of the army robert page recently denied a 
request to increase diversion of great lakes water through the 
illinois river to the mississippi saying the greater flow would 
raise the level on the river at st louis only six inches to a foot 
not enough to benefit shipping 
we think six inches to a foot at st louis would be a big 
help farrell said we just dont think its needed yet but 
when the time comes if sacrificing an inch on the great lakes for 
six inches to a foot can save the mississippi system i think it 
will be accepted by everybody 
</TEXT>
