<TEXT>
anglican bishops from throughout the 
world agreed overwhelmingly that the thorny issue of consecrating 
women as bishops and ordaining them as priests should not splinter 
the anglican communion 
they voted monday night for a carefully worded compromise 
resolution that was designed to keep their churches together 
despite deep divisions on the issue 
the bishops representing 70 million anglicans in 164 countries 
said the churches must respect one anothers decisions and 
attitudes and maintain communications with other bishops regardless 
of gender or viewpoint 
the voting by a show of hands was 42328 with 19 abstentions 
the us episcopal church a member of the anglican communion 
and the canadian and new zealand anglicans are considering 
consecrating woman bishops this year they have admitted more than 
1000 women to the priesthood in the past 11 years 
the 27 anglican chuches worldwide are selfgoverning they look 
to the lambeth conference for guidance but the conference which is 
holding its first meeting in canterbury in 10 years cannot give 
them orders 
the extent of the bishops anxiety was shown in a secret ballot 
by 277187 they defeated a call to the churches to refrain from 
consecrating a woman as bishop because of the damage it would do 
to the anglican communion 
the successful compromise was moved by conference participants 
who spent most of the first two weeks of the threeweek gathering 
discussing and drafting it the conference ends sunday aug 7 
the defeated resolution was proposed by archbishop donald 
robinson of sydney australia who wants to keep the priesthood and 
episcopate allmale and who said he wanted the secret ballot 
robinson said a woman bishop was contrary to the explicit 
teaching of the new testament and threatened a fundamental 
breach of scripture faith and order 
south african bishop george swartz of kimberley and kuruman 
supported him swartz said that while the women priests movement 
was right to say that many would be hurt if women were not 
consecrated bishops many more will be hurt if they are 
margaret hewitt of england who attended the conference as a 
member of the anglican consultative council was the only woman to 
speak in the debate 
she opposed women being priests and bishops saying not all 
the women of the anglican communion are convinced that womens 
ordination is acceptable desirable or appropriate the anglican 
communion has seemed for some time to be the anglican confusion 
but bishop edmond l browning presiding bishop of the us 
episcopal church said it would be only a matter of time before 
women are elected bishops in his church 
this robinsons resolution misrepresents what women have 
learned about ministry and what we have learned from these women 
it ignores the maturity we have achieved and the gifts we have been 
given and share he said 
in failing to reflect what we have forgotten and what we have 
learned it invites mischief rebellion and anarchy in so doing 
it would foster what it seeks to avoid it would usher in 
disunity 
bishop of london graham leonard the leading opponent of women 
priests in the church of england said he would vote for the 
compromise because it was realistic and honest 
archbishop of cape town desmond tutu said he supported women 
priests and women bishops but regretted the issue was overshadowing 
questions of justice and poverty 
archbishop of canterbury robert runcie said before the vote that 
whichever way the count went he would take up the compromise 
resolutions recommendation to appoint a commission the commission 
will examine relations between anglican churches and prepare 
guidelines for them once a woman is consecrated bishop 
runcie is spiritual head of the church of england and presides 
over the conference as the world anglican leader 
he warned that even if the conference passed robinsons 
resolution we have no guarantee that all churches will heed it 
</TEXT>
