<TEXT>
usmediated talks on peace in southern africa 
opened here today and south africas foreign minister said his 
country offered to withdraw troops from southwest africa starting 
nov 1 
foreign minister pik botha said in johannesburg that the 
proposal also called for elections in southwest africa also known 
as namibia on june 1 next year 
it follows that the total withdrawal of cuban troops from 
angola will be completed by june 1 1989 botha said 
the talks the fifth round of closeddoor negotiations that 
started in may in london are being held in genevas bunkerlike 
international conference center the us team and the joint 
angolancuban delegation arrived ahead of the south africans 
a us spokesman art skop said us officials would maintain a 
news embargo until a news conference planned by chester crocker 
the us assistant secretary of state for african affairs after 
completion of the talks here 
hopes have been buoyed by an agreement announced in new york 
july 20 on a set of 14 principles designed to establish the basis 
of peace in the region 
crocker who takes part in the talks as a mediator has 
described the july 20 accord as an important step but has 
warned that a great many hard and difficult compromises have yet 
to be achieved 
the accord was the first joint document accepted by the three 
parties locked in an undeclared war since 1975 the principles 
include an end to south african administration of southwest africa 
and the withdrawal of all cuban troops from angola 
south african angolan and cuban military commanders who met in 
a fourth round of talks late last month on cape verde off the west 
african coast were reported to have made significant progress 
toward the disengagement and withdrawal provisions 
the geneva talks were expected to focus on timetables for 
military disengagement in southern angola and for the eventual 
withdrawal of all cuban troops from angola and of south african 
troops from namibia they are also to agree on provisions ensuring 
unmonitored compliance with the withdrawal schedules 
comments from other parties directly involved in the talks 
ranged from cautious optimism voiced by south african officials to 
cuban president fidel castros statement last week that the talks 
are on the threshold of a political solution 
soviet deputy foreign minister anatoly adamyshin who on monday 
completed two days of preliminary consultations with crocker later 
told reporters chances are good of a settlement in the nearest 
future 
moscow is not directly involved but has been regularly consulted 
by the united states both superpowers have spoken of a growing 
convergence of views on the regional issues 
south africas mandate over southwest africa was terminated by 
the united nations in 1966 but in defiance of several un 
security council resolutions it has retained control of the 
country which possesses considerable mineral wealth 
cuban troops estimated by us officials to total up to 50000 
have helped the marxist angolan government to fight unita the 
rebel movement of jonos which receives military aid from south 
africa and the united states 
angola has also been used as a base by swapo the south west 
africa peoples organization that has been waging an armed struggle 
for namibian independence since 1966 
swapo and unita are not parties to the agreement but spokesmen 
for both have welcomed it 
