american and filipino negotiators 
tuesday resumed talks on the status of us military bases but gave 
no indication of progress on the issue of compensation for the use 
of the bases 
after a meeting lasting more than two hours the two panels 
issued a statement saying they would meet again wednesday they 
refused to answer questions 
tuesdays session was the first since talks broke off a week ago 
according to the statement the negotiators discussed 
compensation the main problem as well as security around the 
sites and the issue of criminal jurisdiction over us troops 
filipino officials said last week that us inflexibility over 
compensation was responsible for the interruption in the talks 
the united states pays the philippines 180 million in military 
and economic aid each year in exchange for the use of clark air 
base subic bay naval base and four smaller facilities 
sources close to the talks said the filipinos demand a raise of 
at least 12 billion but the americans have refused the sources 
who spoke on condition of anonymity said the americans were 
willing to increase compensation only by 360 million 
the americans have proposed that the philippine side also 
consider as compensation the 500 million the bases spend annually 
in salaries to filipino employees and on local purchases the 
sources said 
after announcing the resumption of the talks tuesday foreign 
secretary raul manglapus said our position has already been 
subjected to change and we are not about to change it again 
a source who asked not to be identified said that during 
tuesdays session us ambassador nicholas platt and manglapus 
secluded themselves from the rest of the negotiatiors to discuss 
the question of compensation 
the sources said the americans were reluctant to agree to a 
drastic increase in compensation because of uncertainty over the 
status of the bases after their lease expires in 1991 
the lease may be extended by a formal treaty ratified by 
twothirds of the 23member senate where opposition to the bases 
is strong 
the senate in june approved a bill banning nuclear weapons and 
nuclear powered ships from philippine territory the united states 
opposes such legislation because of its policy refusing to confirm 
or deny the presence of us nuclear weapons 
president corazon aquino whose term expires in 1992 has 
pledged to honor the current agreement but refuses to say whether 
she will support an extension 
the talks are part of negotiations that began four months ago to 
review a 1947 agreement giving the americans the right to operate 
military bases in the philippines 
