<TEXT>
the nations fire deaths shrank just a fraction 
last year to 5810 the sixth year that preventive strategies 
failed to make a significant dent in the death toll the national 
fire protection association said tuesday 
the number of civilians who died in 1987 decreased less than 1 
percent from 1986s total of 5850 deaths according to the report 
compiled by the quincybased association firefighter deaths were 
not included in the totals 
reasons for the sixyear plateau in the death toll include 
waning interest in home safety a slowing in development of fire 
retardant home products which made significant advances in the 
last decade and growth in the highrisk populations of the elderly 
and the very young said dr john r hall jr the associations 
director of fire analysis and research 
were somewhat grasping at explanations too hall said 
fire is so complicated that you cant say for sure you know 
whats driving it weve reached a point where those national 
strategies like smoke detectors that were big enough and effective 
enough have leveled off 
home fires killed 4570 people last year down 18 percent from 
4655 in 1986 but they still accounted for 786 percent of all 
fire deaths 
since 1984 there has been little progress in installing smoke 
detectors and about onethird of those already in place are 
inoperable many because of dead batteries hall said 
fires caused by smoking materials remain the leading cause of 
fatal home blazes hall said the most common fires are caused by 
cigarettes smoldering in couches or chairs he said 
outdoor fires were up 10 percent with 56000 more brush grass 
wildland crop and timber fires an increase partly blamed on 
drought conditions 
youve got an arson problem in outdoor fires youve got a lot 
of carelessness then if you drop the weather situation on top of 
that what might have been a small fire turns into a large fire 
the south led all regions with a fire death rate of 290 per 
million population a regional rate that was 211 percent higher 
than the national average of 239 per million the higher incidence 
of fire deaths in the south is partly due to its large population 
of rural poor hall said 
the number of civilians injured in fires totaled 28215 in 1987 
a 52 percent increase from the previous year that brought figures 
back to the levels of 198485 
the northeast region had the highest civilian fire injury rate 
with 1264 fire injuries per million population but that was 
similar to other regions the report said 
property damage increased 49 percent to 704 billion in 
keeping with inflation the report said 
breaking the impasse on fire deaths will require more widespread 
education programs renewed attention to home smoke detectors 
wider use of residential sprinklers and improvements in products 
typically involved in home fatal fires such as cigarettes and 
lighters said michael j karter jr a senior statistician with 
the association and author of the report 
national fire prevention week in october will focus on 
installing and maintaining smoke detectors hall said 
our biggest obstacle right now is trying to break through that 
misguided belief in personal invulnerability all we can do is 
point to the numbers 
