differences with the military over the communist insurgency have 
weakened the ability of the roman catholic church to influence a 
government it helped catapult to power more than two years ago 
in february 1986 priests and nuns heeded the call of manila 
archbishop cardinal jaime l sin and poured into the streets to 
support the militarycivilian uprising that toppled president 
ferdinand marcos and propelled corazon aquino into office 
the church traditionally has played a strong role in the 
philippines where more than 85 percent of the 59 million people 
are catholic priests in asias only christian country still wield 
considerable influence over the daily lives of parishoners 
but the church now finds its influence on government policy 
reduced especially on the issue of the 19year communist 
insurgency 
the ranks of catholic clergy and laity are split between 
staunchly anticommunist conservatives and those who support many 
of the proclaimed reformist goals of the rebels 
the military has accused many priests and nuns of actively 
supporting the those fighting for the communist new peoples army 
despite the anticommunist stands of sin and others priests from 
the communistdominated christians for national liberation lead 
guerrilla units 
meanwhile military influence over the government has grown 
steadily in the wake of a halfdozen coup attempts put down by 
loyal members of the armed forces 
the clearest sign of the churchs declining influence on 
official policy has been mrs aquinos response to a call by the 
catholic bishops conference of the philippines for a resumption of 
peace talks with the rebel national democratic front 
last month the 115member conference called for a restart of 
peace negotiations which collapsed in january 1987 defense 
secretary fidel ramos has opposed peace talks saying they would 
only serve to give the rebels a propaganda forum 
mrs aquino herself a catholic made no reference to the 
bishops call in last months state of the nation address in 
which she outlined her agenda for the coming year 
instead she said the rebels refusal to lay down their arms had 
given her government the moral basis for war mrs aquino said 
earlier she was amenable to new talks but the rebels must make the 
first move 
the bishops call for talks with the insurgests reflects the 
growing falling out by the church with the aquino government 
columnist amando doronila said in a commentary in the manila 
chronicle newspaper he said the bishops position is certain to 
put pressure on the government to reassess its relationship with 
the church one of mrs aquinos most powerful allies in the 
struggle to overthrow the marcos regime doronila said 
rep venancio garduce former attorney for the conferences 
national secretariat for social action blamed the decline of the 
churchs influence on the inability of its collective leadership to 
assert a strong unified position on key issues 
despite its size however the church has been unable to forge a 
common stand on many issues because it lacks a clearly acknowledged 
leader each diocese technically is independent and answerable only 
to the vatican 
in the may 1987 senate elections sin urged voters to reject 
leftist candidates whom he branded as lepers and openly 
endorsed 11 other candidates angering some bishops as well as 
influential laymen 
in the same election garduce noted that the bishops conference 
lobbied for enactment of a farreaching land reform bill proposed 
last year in the house of representatives 
many prominent legislators including mrs aquinos brother 
rep jose cojuangco opposed the house measure instead the house 
and senate in june approved a compromise version which church 
leaders still accepted 
the church can always adapt garduce said it is too 
compromising 
garduce said the bishops concerned over the governments 
deference to the military backed out of supporting the original 
land reform bill because of army allegations that the church had 
been infiltrated by the communists 
last year the military charged that the churchs social action 
secretariat which coordinates welfare programs was diverting 
funds to the new peoples army 
after an investigation the bishops decided to reorganize the 
secretariat 
the church should be liberational in its approach garduce 
said but then the institutional church probably is aware that 
there will be problems in case this thrust will be continued 
some bishops have complained that the military often charges 
catholic clergy with supporting the rebels simply because of their 
work with the poor 
we regret that our people who are engaged in the work for 
philippine christian communities or social action work are 
suspected sometimes manila bishop teodoro bacani said after a 
recent meeting with military authorities 
</TEXT>
