<TEXT>
this summers wildfires 
are exciting scientists over the prospect of a wilderness 
laboratory while dismaying tourism officials faced with fewer 
visitors to the oldest national park 
the fires also have touched off a lively debate about how much 
man should interfere with natures ways in the west 
there is a great scientific interest in this because there 
will be a tremendous release of forage and habitat for wildlife 
yellowstone superintendent robert barbee said tuesday on the 
other hand if you are making your living on tourism you dont 
want to impede tourism to the area 
thats the horns of our dilemma barbee said 
indeed while scientists wait eagerly to reach charred 
backcountry areas to study the effects of the parks most 
extraordinary fire assault in three centuries wyoming and 
yellowstone officials are trying to get the word out that the park 
remains open 
most fires they emphasize are burning in the parks 
backcountry and only two frontcountry areas the grant village 
complex and lewis lake campground near the parks south entrance 
have been closed by the fire 
yellowstone is keeping a relatively normal operation although 
we have minor disruptions from time to time barbee said we 
have thousands of people here the hotels are full the campgrounds 
are full and people havent left yet 
fires that have burned in the park since june now involve some 
140000 acres although not all of the land within fire lines has 
burned creating a mosaic of burned and unburned areas 
and thats the way these forests have already proceeded 
said barbee the fire process has always played itself this way 
throughout the west 
its a rebirth said john varley park biologist one of 
the public perceptions thats hard to deal with is all this talk of 
destruction devastation and damage 
to the ecologist those are all inappropriate terms it is 
really rebirth and renewal it is the end of one cycle of life and 
the beginning of the next varley said 
such fires eliminate old underbrush and stimulate new growth 
while clearing land for wildlife forage 
what is left behind is a rich mosaic of old growth and new 
growth barbee said what occurs then is a whole host of 
different organisms are on the scene it will be black this year 
next year it will be a carpet of green it is opening habitat that 
has been closed for a couple of hundred years 
it is all part of this dynamic process that occurs in nature 
so what is destruction for one person is a reason for champagne 
corks to pop for the next 
nevertheless publicity generated by the blazes is discouraging 
some tourists according to wyoming travel commission director gene 
bryan 
i dont think there is any question the fires are beginning to 
have an impact he said initially with those folks who were 
already on the road and still planning to go it didnt seem to 
have any immediate impact we are beginning to feel it now in some 
key areas 
yellowstone tourism surveys show that when the south entrance 
closed july 23 the parks overall visitation dropped about 20 
percent from 1987 levels 
to combat the perception that the park and northwestern wyoming 
are inaccessible the travel commission is running 60second radio 
advertisements in salt lake city omaha neb and des moines 
iowa to announce that the parks major facilities and attractions 
are open 
the commission has also asked wyomings congressional delegation 
to consider taping public service announcements and to ask 
president reagan to tape one as well 
some groups are taking exception to contentions by the us 
forest service and park service that the fires are good for the 
area 
a number of people have criticized both agencies for their 
policy of allowing naturally caused fires to burn particularly in 
the park and in the bridgerteton national forest 
however because of this summers extremely dry conditions the 
agencies are fighting most new fires regardless of how they started 
park policies do allow for a change in the practice of allowing 
natural fires to burn depending on the conditions a point keith 
hamilton a wyoming farm bureau official in big horn county finds 
difficult to understand 
park and forest officials have been telling the public they 
feel fires are a natural occurrence and should be allowed to 
burn hamilton said but for some strange reason they place 
several hundred firefighters on the line their real policy is 
still a mystery i think they would like to have their cake and eat 
it too 
