<TEXT>
orders to us factories for manufactured 
goods advanced in june at the fastest rate in more than 17 years a 
55 percent increase that reflected strong demand for civilian and 
military aircraft the government said tuesday 
the commerce department said orders for both durable and 
nondurable goods hit a record 22984 billion in june following a 
07 percent decline in may 
it was the biggest onemonth increase since a 68 percent rise 
in december 1970 and left economists impressed with the continued 
showing of strength by american manufacturing 
even after you take out defense and civilian aircraft it was 
a very nice number said david wyss chief financial economist 
for data resources inc the manufacturing sector is now 
competitive in world markets 
american manufacturers suffered through lean years earlier in 
the decade because of a huge trade deficit caused by shrinking 
export sales and a big surge in imports the administration 
launched an effort in 1985 to devalue the dollar as a way of making 
imports more expensive and boosting the competitiveness of us 
goods overseas 
the june orders report is another indication that the 
industrial side of the economy is close to a boom said allen 
sinai chief economist of the boston co the strength and 
momentum in orders suggests that the capital spending boom we have 
had will keep going though the rest of the year 
much of the overall strength in the economy in the first half of 
1988 has come from the improvement in the trade deficit and a big 
rise in business investment as manufacturers expanded production 
facilities to meet the rising export demand 
the june orders increase came from a 101 billion rise in 
transportation orders which jumped to 382 billion 359 percent 
over the may level the increase included a 52 billion rise in 
demand for military aircraft and a 46 billion rise in 
shipbuilding and tanks 
overall the volatile defense category shot up 786 percent the 
biggest increase since december 1982 without the rise in military 
demand total orders would have risen by a smaller but still 
healthy 27 percent 
the category of nondefense capital goods rose 132 percent to 
3576 billion reflecting in large part the increase in civilian 
aircraft orders most placed with the seattlebased boeing co 
total orders for durable goods items expected to last three or 
more years rose 94 percent to 1259 billion this represented a 
slight upward revision from an advance report a week ago that put 
the increase in durable goods at 88 percent 
orders for primary metals such as steel fell by 33 percent the 
only major sector to post a decline during the month 
orders for nondurable goods rose 12 percent to 10403 
billion reflecting increases in demand for food clothing paper 
and petroleum products 
shipments of manufactured goods rose 15 percent in june to 
2206 billion with over half of that increase coming in the 
durable goods sector 
