<TEXT>
south africa on tuesday 
proposed a ceasefire next month in the angolan war that would lead 
to a withdrawal of foreign troops from angola and independence for 
southwest africa by next june 
foreign minister pik botha speaking in the capital of pretoria 
said south african delegates made the offer tuesday in geneva 
where a new round of peace talks began 
the talks involve south africa angola cuba and us mediators 
the proposal marked the first time south africa has offered a 
specific date for granting independence to southwest africa also 
known as namibia and was seen as a major development in efforts to 
resolve the 13yearold angolan war 
if these proposals are accepted it is the south african 
governments firm belief that there will be no losers botha said 
the sovereignty of angola will be without question southwest 
africa will have gained independence and peace will have been 
restored he said 
botha said that if the ceasefire offer is accepted south 
africa would withdraw its estimated 3000 troops from southern 
angola by sept 1 
on nov 1 south africa would begin withdrawing from southwest 
africa under the guidelines of un resolution 435 which calls for 
independence in the territory 
botha said the south african proposal envisions elections in 
southwest africa on june 1 1989 provided cuba has withdrawn its 
estimated 50000 troops from angola by the same date 
cuba and angola did not immediately comment on the proposal and 
botha said he could not say how they had responded at the geneva 
talks 
cuban troops are in angola supporting the countrys marxist 
government south africa and the united states support the rebels 
of the national union for the total independence of angola unita 
the south african proposal calls for the ceasefire to be 
monitored by committees established at the current round of talks 
in geneva bothas statement did not specify who would do the 
monitoring although in the past he has proposed a un presence 
botha said that if a ceasefire were to begin aug 10 it would 
give un officials almost three months to prepare for south 
africas withdrawal from southwest africa under the terms of 
resolution 435 
south africa backed by the united states has insisted that 
independence for southwest africa must be linked with a cuban 
troop withdrawal from angola 
cuba and angola have suggested a fouryear timetable for the 
cuban withdrawal while the south africans and the united states 
are seeking a much shorter time period 
south africas mandate over southwest africa was terminated by 
the united nations in 1966 but in defiance of several un 
resolutions it has retained control of the country which 
possesses considerable mineral wealth 
among other issues addressed by the south african proposal are 
the southwest africa peoples organization whose guerrillas 
have been fighting for independence for 22 years south africa says 
they must stop launching raids into southwest africa from their 
bases in southern angola 
african national congress bases in angola south africa says 
the anc the main black group fighting to overthrow south africas 
white government has seven major military bases in angola and the 
pretoria government wants those bases closed down 
financial assistance for namibia south africa spends billions 
of dollars annually on southwest africa it is looking for someone 
else to help the territory pay its bills and has suggested the 
five permanent members of the united nations security council 
the south african plan does not mention unita the groups 
leader jonas savimbi wants a powersharing accord with the 
angolan government but the countrys marxist leaders have so far 
refused to negotiate with the guerrilla movement 
none of the negotiating teams in geneva made any comments 
following tuesdays session the talks were scheduled to continue 
wednesday and thursday 
the geneva talks are the fifth round of negotiations started in 
may participants agreed last month on a basic set of 14 principles 
that would lead to the withdrawal of all foreign forces from angola 
and the granting of independence to namibia no timetable was 
agreed on 
