<TEXT>
a list of the most soughtafter books in the 
soviet union this summer shows readers are clamoring for works like 
anatoly rybakovs children of the arbat and other novels born 
in the age of glasnost or released after years on the censors 
shelves 
the government newspaper izvestia ranked the most popular works 
of literature in an article that urged larger printings of books 
both in hardbound novel form for library sales and in the 
circulation of monthly magazines that serialize major books 
izvestia said monday it determined the 12 most popular books in 
the soviet union based on waiting lists at library reading halls 
where soviets can sign up for a turn to read the works on the 
premises 
some books can be checked out of libraries but works with an 
especially strong following are kept at the libraries to prevent 
theft fines for books that arent returned are a fraction of what 
it might cost on the black market 
most of the books occupying the top spots on the soviet list 
compiled by izvestia are stories written years ago but banned by 
authorities or held back by the authors for fear of censorship 
children of the arbat written two decades ago and is the 
most popular book among soviet readers according to the newspaper 
it takes the reader into the life of a student persecuted and 
exiled during the 1930s under josef stalin it was published last 
month in the united states by little brown and co 
stalins repressions feature in several of the best sellers 
including no 2 white clothing about soviet scientists 
manipulation of genetic research in the late 1940s and no 6 the 
golden cloud slumbered recounting the horrors perpetrated on 
soviet ethnic groups exiled for alleged collaboration with the 
nazis during world war ii 
other works popular with readers now were held back by soviet 
censors for decades like boris pasternaks doctor zhivago a 
sympathetic account of the hardships endured by an aristocratic 
doctor following the 1917 bolshevik revolution izvestia said 
pasternaks work for which he won the 1958 nobel prize is the 
fourth most popular book among soviets it was released two years 
ago in a limited printing mostly sold to foreigners for hard 
currency and early this year was serialized in the monthly magazine 
novy mir 
serial printings in masscirculation magazines like novy mir 
offer the best access to new releases for most soviets even the 
most popular books are issued in relatively small quantities in 
comparison with demand 
but the periodicals are usually available only by subscription 
and they are relatively costly for soviet pensioners and others 
with low incomes 
izvestia complained that soviet publishers waste their limited 
resources producing political tomes and brochures that few want to 
read as a result waiting lists for popular books at public 
libraries have more than tripled in the past year the newspaper 
said 
izvestia pressed state publishers to redirect resources so the 
avid reading public would not have to waste so much time waiting in 
line for books 
economists have calculated that for various goods and services 
we stand in lines for 65 billion manhours a year the newspaper 
said of the soviet unions 284 million citizens but the time we 
have to spend in pursuit of culture is no less expensive 
part of the increase in interest at public libraries has been 
the release of thousands of previously banned works 
the newspaper soviet culture reported in march that glavlit the 
state body which since 1922 has been responsible for censorship is 
conducting a review of 6000 books held in special detention 
storehouses 
of the 4000 titles reviewed by spring 3500 had been returned 
to library shelves the newpaper reported 
izvestia said no 3 in popularity among soviets is favorite 
by valentin pikul about one of catherine the greats lovers 
grigory potemkin 
following no 4 doctor zhivago was alexander beks the new 
appointment which portrays a bureaucrats fall from power 
