<TEXT>
the united states is examining creation of an 
international peacekeeping force as a way to prevent the khmer 
rouge from resuming power in cambodia the state department said 
tuesday 
the proposal is one of several that were explored in talks last 
week between the vietnameseinstalled government in phnom penh and 
three guerrilla factions seeking to overthrow the rulers said 
spokeswoman phyllis oakley 
other state department officials said discussions on the 
possibility of a peacekeeping force were in a very preliminary 
stage and thus it was too early to tell which nations including 
the united states might supply troops for it 
a peacekeeping force would be designed to take over from the 
vietnamese troops who are scheduled to withdraw from the country by 
1990 vietnam and other countries are fearful that the vacuum left 
by the pullout would allow the murderous khmer rouge group to take 
over cambodia 
the khmer rouge who were accused of killing hundreds of 
thousands of cambodians during their threeyear rule were replaced 
by vietnam when it invaded cambodia in 1978 
some khmer rouge found refuge in china and neighboring thailand 
while others stayed in cambodia and joined the antigovernment 
rebels 
china has reportedly promised to cease its support for the khmer 
rouge if vietnam pulls out 
in a television interview tuesday rep stephen solarz dny 
urged the united states and other western governments to prevent 
the reemergence of the khmer rouge which he said could very 
easily lead to another holocaust in cambodia 
i think the west needs to do much more than what it has been 
doing in order to prevent such a dreadful eventuality from coming 
about solarz chairman of the house foreign affairs subcommittee 
on asian and pacific affairs said on the cbs this morning 
program 
we would support any reasonable measures to prevent the return 
of the khmer rouge and to safeguard the right of the cambodian 
people to choose their own destiny said mrs oakley 
but the shape of a final settlement depends on direct 
negotiations between the key parties and must be in the context of 
agreement on complete withdrawal of vietnamese troops she added 
the firstever talks between the sides last week in indonesia 
failed to achieve a breakthough although working groups were set up 
to negotiate and make recommendations by years end 
testifying before the senate foreign relations committee on 
tuesday another state department official said an international 
peacekeeping force is one of several options being considered to 
prevent the khmer rouge from again taking power in cambodia 
crafting a solution will not be easy said david lambertson 
deputy assistant secretary of state for south east asia the 
khmer rouge remain probably the most militarily powerful of the 
cambodian factions 
lambertson said options advanced by cambodias neighbors and by 
prince norodom sihanouk the nations former ruler include holding 
internationally supervised elections 
we cannot imagine the cambodian people would willingly vote 
for the return of the khmer rouge lambertson said 
he said other options include removing pol pot and other khmer 
rouge leaders most responsible for crimes against the cambodian 
people and disarming all cambodian political factions 
also under consideration he said are a cutoff of the flow of 
arms from outside cambodias borders we believe some combination 
of these or other approaches could prove effective lambertson 
said 
lambertson said the united states also believes it is important 
to maintain diplomatic pressure against vietnam until it has 
completely withdrawn its troops from cambodia 
he reiterated that the reagan administration opposes legislation 
under discussion in congress to establish diplomatic interest 
sections in hanoi and washington to expand contacts between the two 
nations 
lambertson said such a step now would be seen as a major 
political victory by hanoi and a sign by the noncommunist 
resistance inside cambodia as a deeply discouraging signal of a 
weakened american commitment 
under pressure from the soviet union vietnam has promised to 
pull out its estimated 120000 troops by 1990 but has demanded 
assurances that the khmer rouge will not return 
the soviet union and china have scheduled an unusual meeting in 
peking later this month to discuss a cambodian settlement 
china has told the united states that soviet cooperation on the 
cambodia issue could remove one of the remaining obstacles to a 
toplevel summit meeting between the two communist giants who have 
been at odds for more than 30 years 
