<TEXT>
a federal magistrate tuesday refused a 
request by two newspapers to release documents relating to a search 
by federal agents of three unisys corp offices as part of the 
pentagon procurement probe 
us magistrate j earl cudd agreed with the governments 
position that release of search warrants affidavits and other 
documents would jeopardize the federal investigation into possible 
illegalities in defense department contracting 
the court finds that preserving the sensitivity of the ongoing 
criminal investigation is a sufficiently compelling interest to 
justify denial of public access cudd wrote in his decision 
the star tribune and st paul pioneer press dispatch had sought 
access to the documents 
were going to appeal said tim mcguire star tribune 
managing editor its a matter of important public interest the 
progress of this investigation demands press scrutiny 
cudd said the sealed material contains sensitive information 
identifying people who are the focus of the investigation their 
activities and programs being investigated as well as documents 
the government hopes to obtain 
were this information made public there is a substantial 
probability the investigation would be irreparably damaged cudd 
wrote 
he said he was concerned about the possibility that documents 
might be destroyed and witnesses might attempt to tailor their 
accounts of events if they knew the scope and direction of the 
investigation 
the court is also concerned that disclosure would interfere 
with the legitimate privacy of persons whose conversations were 
intercepted during authorized wiretaps and who are therefore 
mentioned in the affidavits but who upon further investigation 
may not be criminally culpable cudd wrote 
although cudd acknowledged that release of the documents would 
be in the public interest he found that disclosure at this 
preliminary stage would unnecessarily subject innocent third 
parties to the risk of serious injury 
patrick schiltz attorney for the star tribune argued at a july 
22 hearing that keeping the search warrants and affidavits sealed 
is pointless because any reasonably informed observer could 
make a good guess as to what is involved in the investigation 
simply by reading newspapers 
but assistant us attorney thor anderson told the magistrate 
that because the information was printed in newspapers doesnt 
make it accurate 
fbi agents on june 13 searched three offices at the unisys plant 
in eagan unisys plants elsewhere in the country and offices of 
other major defense contractors in 11 other states and the district 
of columbia 
the eagan facilities of unisys defense systems make mainframe 
computers for the us defense department no weapons are made at 
the facilities and most of the computers are used by the navy 
other news organizations are seeking release of similar 
documents around the country 
last week the new head of the minneapolis fbi office said he 
expects indictments and guilty pleas in the twin cities area as 
part of the national defense procurement investigation 
