<TEXT>
a community college has been fined 3000 
as a result of an investigation ordered after the death of a 
student who was given the wrong liquid to drink in a laboratory 
experiment 
pierce college was cited monday for 10 violations of safety 
procedures and fined for failing to implement a program to inform 
employees about hazardous chemicals said barbara dunn of the state 
department of labor and industries 
the school failed to carry out a hazardous communication 
program for handling chemicals 10 months after first being cited 
for that shortcoming ms dunn said the college had the program in 
writing but had not implemented it she said 
school president brent knight said safety programs had been 
improved and the fine would be appealed 
the investigation followed the death of dawn collins 29 of 
puyallup on june 5 four days after she drank a solution during a 
urinalysis experiment in an anatomy and physiology class 
the experiment called for a simple saline solution basically 
salt water but instead she was mistakenly given a solution 
containing sodium azide a preservative 
richard montecucco an assistant attorney general investigating 
the case said a lab technician apparently used a premixed saline 
solution containing sodium azide rather than mixing the solution 
using salt tablets and water 
ms dunn said her agency which investigates accidents involving 
workers was not legally required to reinspect the school after the 
womans death since she was not a college employee but she said 
it decided to do so because it was very obvious the school had 
not complied with the order issued in august 
the latest citations were praised by jack connelly an attorney 
for the collins family who said he was preparing a lawsuit against 
the college 
its very apparent in dawn collins case that the appropriate 
measures were not followed and somebody should have known what was 
in that container connelly said 
investigators found improperly labeled chemicals at the school 
their 11page report said 
a halfgallon metal container with tape marked poison on the 
side was found in the art building and an unmarked brass can of 
lithotine a toxic mineral spirit with pine oil was in the art 
building storage room ms dunn said 
one violation said college employees including lab workers 
were not given information and training on hazardous chemicals in 
their work areas 
knight however contended that officials of the 8000student 
school in the suburbs south of the city had been working to meet 
the requirements of a workers right to know law adopted in 
1986 the law requires employers to inform employees of hazardous 
chemicals in the workplace and have available information on 
procedures for chemical emergencies 
the state agency fined the college 240 last september for seven 
violations including lack of programs for accident prevention or 
handling hazardous materials college officials appealed and the 
fine was reduced to 60 which was paid in november said agency 
spokesman rolland lund 
the first citations resulted from an investigation after an 
employee was burned when an electric spraypainter came in contact 
with flammable liquid 
last month a washington state patrol bomb squad removed 13 
liters more than four gallons of hazardous outdated ether from 
the schools science labs during a cleanout of lab chemicals 
