<TEXT>
the house voted 34654 tuesday to require a 
tenfold increase in the amount power companies must pay to victims 
of an accident at a nuclear generating plant 
despite the proposed jump however critics inside and outside 
congress blasted the plan as corporate bailout that would still 
leave taxpayers and victims footing most of the liability costs of 
a major nuclear accident 
the legislation expected to win senate approval is a 15year 
renewal of the priceanderson act the unique law that limits the 
amount the nuclear power industry would have to pay in damages to 
accident victims 
the law first enacted in 1957 expired a year ago it is the 
only federal statute setting a cap on how much an industry would 
have to pay to victims in this case 710 million 
the housepassed plan would set the industry liability limit at 
71 billion with 160 million covered by private insurance and 
the rest apportioned among the nations utilities owning nuclear 
plants 
if it appeared that damage awards would exceed the limit 
congress would have to come up with legislation to provide the 
additional money needed to compensate victims 
this leaves the government and the taxpayers holding the 
bag said rep dennis eckart dohio these corporate bailout 
amendments perpetuate the most egregious form of taxpayer 
support imaginable 
also attacking the legislation was public citizen the ralph 
naderfounded organization that said government studies have 
suggested that a catastrophic accident at a nuclear power plant 
could cause 100 billion or more in damages 
the priceanderson act is a multibilliondollar annual 
windfall for the nuclear industry which distorts the energy 
marketplace encourages unsafe nuclear facilities and dumps the 
risk of a major accident in the lap of federal taxpayers or the 
victims themselves the organizations ken bossong said in a 
prepared statement 
steve unglesbee director of legislation communications for the 
american nuclear energy council an industry group said in an 
interview that the legislation is a big step forward in 
compensation for victims 
unglesbee said he did not think that the laws renewal by itself 
would signal a revitalization of the nuclear power industry which 
has appeared almost moribund in recent years 
to do this the federal government must streamline the process 
for licensing new nuclear generators and settle on a standardized 
design for nuclear plants according to unglesbee 
barring an accident requiring industry payments to victims 
renewal of the compensationlimit law is not expected to affect 
homeowners electricity rates very much because liability insurance 
costs are a small part of a utilitys operating expenses 
