<TEXT>
chief justice william h rehnquist joined 
other legal experts tuesday in applauding the growing use of 
arbitration and other alternatives to litigation saying they offer 
a new path for justice 
rehnquist told a conference of state chief justices and court 
administrators that the use of nontraditional mechanisms to 
resolve disputes could turn out to be the wave of the future 
unless something is done to bring under control the cost of 
litigation in our courts what we now call alternative dispute 
resolution may become the mainstream for many kinds of cases the 
chief justice said 
rehnquists remarks set the stage for a series of presentations 
and panel discussions on innovative procedures established by the 
various states to encourage mediation and arbitration to resolve 
civil disputes without lengthy court battles 
up to 90 percent of all civil cases are settled before trial 
said carl f bianchi administrative director of idaho state 
courts but what is new is the enthusiastic packaging and 
selling of outofcourt options for settling disputes 
bianchi said there are currently more than 800 such programs 
around the country ranging from ambitious statefinanced systems 
to a canine court in los angeles in which a trained animal handler 
attempts to mediate disputes between dog owners and plaintiffs 
rehnquist said that while the federal courts are trying some 
alternative dispute procedures most of the action is in state 
courts because they have the bulk of the caseload 
they have to be the pioneers in this he said of state 
courts adding that they can serve as laboratories in which legal 
scholars can examine which methods work and which do not 
the chief justice characterized as a bum rap the suggestion 
that alternative options are tantamount to a secondclass system 
of justice 
noting that a firstclass lawsuit can remain tied up in the 
courts for five years and conclude with a lawyer receiving more 
than half the amount recovered rehnquist said it should come as no 
surprise that many wouldbe litigants would prefer a different 
approach 
if alternative dispute resolution can provide a fair system of 
resolving a claim and do it in a reasonable amount of time and at 
reasonable expense it can be the wave of the future he said 
rehnquist also announced that he has appointed a committee of 
the judicial conference of the united states chaired by retired 
justice lewis powell to look into the review process in capital 
punishment cases 
the committee will try to determine whether the combined review 
process of capital sentences in state and federal courts takes too 
much time and whether theres coherence and rationality in the 
process rehnquist said 
</TEXT>
