<TEXT>
two alcohol tankers that burned after a 
headon train collision should have been in the rear of an iowa 
interstate railroad freight train instead of the front company 
officials told federal investigators tuesday 
the tank cars which each contained 20000 gallons of denatured 
alcohol were the second and third cars in the westbound train that 
wrecked saturday killing two crewmen 
they were not placed as they should have been placed according 
to instructions that the interstate iowa railroad had given said 
edward dobranetski of the national transportation safety board 
dobranetski declined to speculate whether correct placement 
would have prevented the outbreak of fire which forced a twoday 
evacuation of 2000 residents in the altoona area just northeast of 
des moines 
investigators also confirmed tuesday that the crash happened at 
1145 am dobranetski said monday that the eastbound train had 
been ordered to stay in the altoona switching yard until 1201 pm 
interviews with the surviving crewman from the eastbound train 
showed the conductor and the engineer believed they had left early 
but dobranetski said investigators still arent sure if the 
train had left the altoona yard because there arent any signs 
showing yard limits 
federal investigators plan to wrap up their onsite 
investigation friday the ntsb is not expected to rule on the 
accidents cause for six to nine months 
iowa interstate officials hoped to resume traffic on the line 
tuesday night 
the crash occurred on what is known by railroad workers as 
dark territory a rail line lacking lighted signals to warn of 
oncoming traffic 
signals could have prevented that dobranetski said 
iowa interstate has been operating without signals because 
previous signal lights were vandalized before the railroad began 
running on the track in 1984 according to dennis shaffer the 
railroads vice president for marketing 
iowa interstate leases the track from heartland rail corp 
heartland attorney scott bannister declined to say whether lighted 
signals would have prevented the crash but noted that iowa 
interstate traffic on the line is much lighter than the traffic of 
the lines previous operator rock island lines 
neil volmer manager of engineering and safety for the iowa 
department of transportations rail division said iowa interstate 
was complying with federal railroad administration regulations by 
running trains via orders transmitted by radio or telephone from 
dispatchers 
