<TEXT>
gillette co has fended off another possible 
takeover attempt by settling lawsuits with coniston partners 
stemming from their bitter proxy fight earlier this year 
as part of the settlement outlined monday gillette will buy 
back an estimated 16 million shares at 45 each or a total of 720 
million 
the deal also contains a standstill agreement under which 
coniston is barred from buying significant numbers of gillette 
shares participating in any proxy contest or otherwise seeking 
control of the company for three years 
the settlement ends conistons suit over the april 21 proxy vote 
it lost to gillette as a result the personal care products giant 
does not face a rerun of the election 
a federal judge said last month he was inclined to order a new 
vote which many observers thought would favor coniston because 
gillette misled stockholders in an advertisement about coniston 
before the election 
under terms of the settlement all gillette stockholders may 
sell one share back to the company at 45 for each seven they own 
gillette officials estimated that 16 million of the companys 
112 million outstanding shares likely would be purchased under the 
settlement 
gillette has relied on standstill agreements and stock buybacks 
in the past to fend off unwanted suitors 
after revlon groups failed bid for gillette in 1986 gillette 
paid 558 million to buy back 92 million shares of stock and got 
revlon chairman ronald o perelman to make a similar standstill 
agreement 
in addition gillette has reached a series of other standstill 
agreements with potential suitors since then the companys failure 
to disclose the agreements during its proxy fight with coniston was 
another issue in its legal dispute with the partnership 
edward froelich an analyst with pershing amp co said monday 
that the latest settlement means gillette management wants to 
keep the status quo but theyre shrinking the capital and diluting 
earnings a bit 
froelich said the company would be able to continue fighting off 
such overtures as long as they keep the earnings rising and they 
have i dont think the stockholders will be too badly off 
gillette stock fell 262 a share to 3750 in composite 
trading monday on the new york stock exchange 
coniston which owns nearly 6 percent of gillettes outstanding 
shares waged the proxy battle earlier this year in an effort to 
win four directors seats and pressure the 12member gillette board 
to sell the company coniston believes a sale would boost the value 
of gillette stock 
gillette filed suit april 14 to block conistons proxy bid on 
the grounds that coniston falsified securities and exchange 
commission filings and did not fully disclose all its investors 
coniston countersued alleging gillette misrepresented the 
partnership in advertisements and mailings to the companys 27000 
shareholders and failed to publicly disclose all companies that had 
expressed interest in buying gillette 
us district court judge mark l wolf ruled in early april that 
gillette inaccurately portrayed coniston in newspaper 
advertisements leading up to the proxy vote in which shareholders 
rejected conistons slate of four director candidates 
paul tierney jr a coniston general partner issued a statement 
monday saying we believe this settlement at this time is in the 
best interests of all concerned 
joan fitzgerald a spokeswoman for gillette maintained that 
all shareholders will benefit from the repurchase agreement and 
said it was similar to the stock buyback plan the company began in 
1986 prior to conistons action 
