<TEXT>
washingtons insurance commissioner on 
tuesday rejected an unfriendly takeover of farmers insurance group 
by batus inc making his state the fourth to do so 
the policyholders could quite possibly lose from the 
acquisition and they do not stand to gain anything from it 
commissioner dick marquardt said in an order turning down the 
takeover proposal 
washington joins oregon idaho and california in rejecting the 
45 billion 63 per share hostile takeover bid arizona has 
approved the takeover and decisions are pending in illinois ohio 
kansas and texas 
ed ives a spokesman for marquardt said an appeal of the order 
was certain batus the us arm of british conglomerate bat 
industries plc has 30 days to appeal to the commissioner 
marquardts decision followed nearly a week of hearings in 
seattle last month as have regulators in other states he 
expressed concern that if it took over farmers there was a 
likelihood batus might drop the companys nonsmoker discounts on 
auto and homeowner policies 
louisville kybased batus is the parent of brown amp williamson 
tobacco corp 
the commissioner also said there was a chance batus would end 
farmers medical malpractice coverage 
farmers withdrawal from this market would have seriously 
adverse anticompetitive effects particularly in the washington 
market and would tend to create a monopoly in that line in 
washington he said 
farmers insurance co of washington based in vancouver and 
farmers new world life headquartered on mercer island are 
affiliates of farmers insurance group of los angeles 
farmers is the states largest auto insurance company writing 
174 percent of the market marquardt said it ranks third in 
homeowner policies 10th in commercial insurance sales and provides 
a quarter of all washington hospitals with their medical 
malpractice coverage 
